SIMPLE: slavery
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Slavery
<hw>Slav"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Slaveries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[See 2d
<er>Slave</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The condition of a slave; the
state of entire subjection of one person to the will of
another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Disguise thyself as thou wilt, still, <qex>slavery</qex>, said I,
still thou art a bitter draught!</q> <rj><qau>Sterne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I wish, from my soul, that the legislature of this state
[Virginia] could see the policy of a gradual abolition of
<qex>slavery</qex>. It might prevent much future mischief.</q>
<rj><qau>Washington.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A condition of subjection or submission
characterized by lack of freedom of action or of will.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The vulgar <qex>slaveries</qex> rich men submit to.</q>
<rj><qau>C. Lever.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a <qex>slavery</qex> that no legislation can abolish, --
the <qex>slavery</qex> of caste.</q> <rj><qau>G. W.
Cable.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The holding of slaves.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Bondage; servitude; inthrallment; enslavement;
captivity; bond service; vassalage.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Slavey</ent>⟦br⟧
